<subsection xml:id="subsec-BinomialPractice">
  <title>Practice Problems</title>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-binomial-nursing">
<title>Nursing</title> 
  <statement>
    <p>
      A nurse educator knows that the probability a nursing student correctly
      performs a sterile dressing change on the first attempt is 0.80.
      Suppose 6 students are selected independently.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>X</m> be the number of students who correctly perform the procedure
      on the first attempt.
    </p>
    <p>
      A. Find the probability that exactly <m>4</m> of the <m>6</m> students
      correctly perform the sterile dressing change on the first attempt.
    </p>
    <p>
      B. Find the probability that at least 4 of the 6 students
      correctly perform the sterile dressing change on the first attempt.
    </p>

  </statement>
  <solution> <title>Exactly 4</title>
    <p>
      Since there are a fixed number of trials <m>n=6</m>, there are two possible outcomes for each (correct or not), the trials are independent, and a constant probability of success for each trial with <m>p=.80</m>, this is a binomial distribution.
    </p>
    <p>
      Thus,
      <m>X \sim \text{Binomial}(n=6,p=0.80)</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The binomial probability formula is
      <m>
        P(X=x)=\binom{n}{x}p^x(q)^{n-x}.
      </m> 
    </p>
    <p>
      For this problem, <m>n=6</m>, <m>x=4</m>, <m>p=0.80</m>, and <m>q=1-p=0.20</m>.
      So,
    </p>
    <p> <m>  P(X=4)=\binom{6}{4}(0.80)^4(0.20)^2.   </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      Compute each part:
      <m>\binom{6}{4}=15</m> ways,
      <m>(0.80)^4=0.4096</m>,
      and
      <m>(0.20)^2=0.04</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Therefore,
      <m>
        P(X=4)=15(0.4096)(0.04)=0.24576.
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      So, the probability that exactly 4 of the 6 students
      correctly perform the sterile dressing change on the first attempt is
      approximately <m>0.2458</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
  <solution> <title>At Least 4</title>
    <p>
      To find the probability that at least 4 of the 6 students correctly perform the sterile dressing change on the first attempt, we need to calculate <m>P(X \geq 4)</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is equivalent to calculating <m>P(X=4) + P(X=5) + P(X=6)</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      We already calculated <m>P(X=4)=0.24576</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      For <m>P(X=5)</m>, using the binomial probability formula:
      <m>
        P(X=5)=\binom{6}{5}(0.80)^5(0.20)^1.
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      Compute each part:
      <m>\binom{6}{5}=6</m> ways,
      <m>(0.80)^5=0.32768</m>,
      and
      <m>(0.20)^1=0.20</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Therefore,
      <m>
        P(X=5)=6(0.32768)(0.20)=0.393216.
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      For <m>P(X=6)</m>, using the binomial probability formula:
      <m>
        P(X=6)=\binom{6}{6}(0.80)^6(0.20)^0.
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      Compute each part:
      <m>\binom{6}{6}=1</m> way,
      <m>(0.80)^6=0.262144</m>,
      and
      <m>(0.20)^0=1</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Therefore,
      <m>
        P(X=6)=1(0.262144)(1)=0.262144.
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      Thus,
      <m>
        P(X \geq 4)=P(X=4)+P(X=5)+P(X=6).
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      Substituting the values:
      <m>
        P(X \geq 4)=0.24576+0.393216+0.262144=0.90112.
      </m>
    </p>
<p>
      So, the probability that at least <m>4</m> of the <m>6</m> students
      correctly perform the sterile dressing change on the first attempt is
      approximately <m>0.9011</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ex-binomial-pathogen">
<title> Pathogen</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A chemist knows that the probability a laboratory test correctly detects a
      pathogen compound in a sample is <m>0.85</m>. Suppose <m>7</m> samples are
      tested independently.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>X</m> be the number of samples for which the test correctly detects
      the targeted pathogen compound.
    </p>
    <p>
      A. Find the probability that exactly 5 of the 7 samples are correctly identified.
    </p>
    <p>
    B.  Find the probability that fewer than 4 of the 7 samples are correctly detected.
    </p>

  </statement>
  <solution> <title>Exactly 5</title>
    <p>
      Since there are a fixed number of trials <m>n=7</m>, each trial has two possible
      outcomes, the trials are independent, and the probability of success is
      constant with <m>p=0.85</m>, this is a binomial distribution.
    </p>
    <p>
      Thus,
      <m>X \sim \text{Binomial}(n=7,p=0.85)</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The binomial probability formula is
      <m>
        P(X=x)=\binom{n}{x}p^x(1-p)^{n-x}.
      </m>
    </p>
    <p> Thus, 
      <m>
        P(X=5)=\binom{7}{5}(0.85)^5(0.15)^2.
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      Compute each part:
      <m>\binom{7}{5}=21</m> ways,
      <m>(0.85)^5\approx 0.4437</m>,
      and
      <m>(0.15)^2=0.0225</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Therefore,
      <m>
        P(X=5)=21(0.4437)(0.0225)\approx 0.2097.
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      So, the probability that exactly 5 of the 7 samples are
      correctly identified is approximately 0.2097.
    </p>
  </solution>
  <solution> <title>Fewer than 4</title>
    <p>
      We want to find <m>P(X \lt 4)</m>, which is the same as <m>P(X \leq 3)</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Using the binomial probability formula:
      <m>
        P(X=0)=\binom{7}{0}(0.85)^0(0.15)^7,
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      Compute each part:
      <m>\binom{7}{0}=1</m> way,
      <m>(0.85)^0=1</m>,
      and
      <m>(0.15)^7\approx 0.0000017</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Therefore,
      <m>
        P(X=0)\approx 1(1)(0.0000017)=0.0000017.
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      Similarly, we can compute the probabilities for <m>X=1,2,3</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Substituting the values:
      <m>
        P(X \lt 4)=P(X=0)+P(X=1)+P(X=2)+P(X=3).
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      Therefore,
      <m>
        P(X \lt 4)\approx 0.0000017+0.00006777+0.00115+0.01088\approx 0.012115.
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      So, the probability that fewer than 4 of the 7 samples are
      correctly detected is approximately 0.0121.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>
