<exercise xml:id="ex-binomial-rainfall">
<title> Rainfall</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A meteorologist knows that the probability of a forecasting model correctly
      predicts rainfall for a given day is <m>0.70</m>. Suppose the model is
      used for <m>8</m> independent days.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>X</m> be the number of days for which the model correctly predicts rainfall.
    </p>
    <p> A. Find the probability that exactly 6 of the 8 daily forecasts correctly predicted rainfall.
    </p>
    <p> B. Find the probability that more than 6 of the 8 daily forecasts correctly predicted rainfall.
    </p>
   <p> C. Find the mean number of days the model correctly predicts rainfall in a sample of 30 days. 
</p>
  </statement>
  <solution><title> Six Days</title>
    <p>
      Since there are a fixed number of trials, each trial has two possible
      Outcomes (rain or not), the trials are independent, and the probability of success is
      constant, this is a binomial distribution.
    </p>
    <p>
      Thus,
      <m>X \sim \text{Binomial}(n=8,p=0.70)</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The binomial probability formula is
      <m>
        P(X=x)=\binom{n}{x}p^x(1-p)^{n-x}.
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      Here,
      <m>n=8</m>,
      <m>x=6</m>,
      and
      <m>p=0.70</m>.
      So,
    </p>
    <p>
      <m>
        P(X=6)=\binom{8}{6}(0.70)^6(0.30)^2.
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      Compute each part:
      <m>\binom{8}{6}=28</m> ways,
      <m>(0.70)^6=0.117649</m>,
      and
      <m>(0.30)^2=0.09</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Therefore,
      <m>
        P(X=6)=28(0.117649)(0.09)\approx 0.2965.
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      So, the probability that exactly 6 of the 8 daily forecasts
      correctly predict rainfall is approximately <m>0.2965</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
<solution> <title> More than 6</title>
<p> We want to find   <m>P(X \gt 6)</m>, which is  <m>    P(X \gt 6)=P(X=7)+P(X=8).
      </m>  </p>
    <p>
      Using the binomial formula    <m>  P(X=x)=\binom{n}{x}p^x(1-p)^{n-x},
      </m>    we calculate each probability.
    </p>
    <p>
      First,
      <m>
        P(X=7)=\binom{8}{7}(0.70)^7(0.30)^1
        =8(0.0823543)(0.30)
        \approx 0.1977.
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      Next,
      <m>
        P(X=8)=\binom{8}{8}(0.70)^8(0.30)^0
        =1(0.05764801)(1)
        =0.0576.
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      Therefore,
      <m>
        P(X \gt 6)=0.1977+0.0576=0.2553.
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      So, the probability that the model correctly predicts rainfall on more
      than 6 of the 8 days is approximately <m>0.2553</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
<solution><title>Mean</title>
<p> We know that <m> p=0.70</m> thus <m>q=0.30</m> and <m>n=30</m></p>
<p> Mean is <m> \mu = np =0.70 \times 30 = 21</m> days </p> 
<p> Variance is <m> \sigma^2 = npq=(30)(0.70)(.30)=6.3 </m> </p>
 <p> Standard deviation is <m> \sigma=\sqrt{6.3}=2.5 </m> </p>
<p> Estimate a mean of 21 correctly predicted rainfalls out of 30 days. The variance is 6.3 with a standard deviation of 2.5 days. </p>
</solution>
